Melania project, but a source with a first-hand view of the goings-on told =
me that Melania herself said she was a fan of Ratner=E2=80=99s work (<em>To=
wer</em> <em>Heist</em>? <em>Red</em> <em>Dragon</em>?) and liked the idea =
that he was an outcast. I suppose that=E2=80=99s plausible, but there were =
others who could have made the connection, such as <strong>Marc Beckman</st=
rong>, Melania=E2=80=99s representative of many years, and the founder of D=
esigners Management Agency.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">A so=
urce told me that Beckman, who had set up the recent <em>Melania</em> book,=
 was acquainted with Ratner through some earlier business dealings involvin=
g a client of his marketing firm. (The company=E2=80=99s website lists past=
 or present clients including the NBA, Warner Bros., Procter &amp; Gamble, =
Gucci, and the New York City Ballet.) Beckman confirmed to me that he handl=
ed the negotiations with bidders, but he did not respond to
other questions.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">There was also the producer of the doc=
,<strong> Fernando Sulichin</strong>, who pulled together financing before =
Amazon was in the picture. Born in Argentina and now living in London, Suli=
chin keeps a low profile and is not widely known in Hollywood. But he has a=
 certain Zelig-like way of turning up in unusual places. In 2015, <strong>S=
ean</strong> <strong>Penn</strong> and the Mexican
American actress <strong>Kate del Castillo</strong> travelled to meet and i=
nterview drug lord <strong>Joaquin =E2=80=9CEl Chapo=E2=80=9D Guzm=C3=A1n</=
strong> at his hideout in Sinaloa and nearly got caught up in a planned gov=
ernment raid. Sulichin was there.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Sulichin also arrange=
d for <strong>Oliver</strong> <strong>Stone</strong> to conduct 20 hours of=
 interviews with <strong>Vladimir Putin</strong>, which became the
four-part Showtime series <em>The Putin Interviews</em>. (Several critics t=
ook issue with Stone for being, in the words of the <em>New York Times</em>=
 review, =E2=80=9Csolicitous, even obsequious=E2=80=9D toward his subject.)=
 =E2=80=9CFernando has remarkable access to powerful people, and I don=E2=
=80=99t know how and why,=E2=80=9D one longtime associate told me. =E2=80=
=9CHe likes being discreet. He doesn=E2=80=99t like headlines.=E2=80=9D Hav=
ing known him for years, this person told me, =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know=
 what=E2=80=99s behind the curtain.=E2=80=9D (For those interested in a
potential meet-up, a source says the producer will be in L.A. this week.)</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"=
>There is some conflict among sources about whether Sulichin was involved w=
ith the Melania doc and then brought in Ratner, or whether it was the other=
 way around. One person who was involved in the bidding told me that he was=
 =E2=80=9Chighly confident=E2=80=9D that Sulichin came first; another sourc=
e close to Sulichin insisted that Ratner brought <em>him</em> into the
project. But a Sulichin associate remembered that the producer had once que=
stioned whether the =E2=80=9Ccoast was clear=E2=80=9D for Ratner to make a =
comeback. (Sulichin did not respond to a request for comment.)</p></div>
