x;">Ratner, after all, was closely associated with one of the biggest scand=
als in recent
Hollywood history. <strong>Charlotte Kirk</strong>, the British aspiring ac=
tress who brought down then-Warner Bros. chairman and C.E.O. <strong>Kevin =
Tsujihara</strong> and NBCUniversal vice chair <strong>Ron Meyer</strong>, =
was able to pursue her Hollywood dreams in the U.S. because, in 2012, Ratne=
r went to bat for her with the Department of Homeland Security. The directo=
r wrote that Kirk, then 20, had =E2=80=9Cremarkable talent=E2=80=9D with a =
=E2=80=9Cunique ability to deliver each of her lines seamlessly.=E2=80=9D K=
irk got
a special visa, but the problem for both Tsujihara and Meyer was that she w=
as very much <em>not</em> in demand. Despite their powerful jobs, their eff=
orts to help her land roles failed.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In 2013, Ratner and=
 Australian billionaire <strong>James Packer</strong>, then Ratner=E2=80=99=
s partner (the =E2=80=9CPac=E2=80=9D in RatPac Entertainment), introduced K=
irk to Tsujihara to celebrate their new $450 million film financing deal
with Warner Bros. Having apparently tired of his own affair with Kirk, acco=
rding to text messages that I previously <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news=
